caption: Tried the vegan meat pizza and we upgraded the vegan mozzarella as well. The cheese was extremely gummy, it grossed me out so much that I only ate one full slice. Absolutely lovely place.

Feedback from someone who has ordered atleast 20+ times in the last one year from them (loyal pizza customer).  1) Food Quality: When they deliver a pizza with full attention, it's amazing. When they don't, it may come with a hair in the pizza bread or a wrong order (in my case, veggie 'manchurian' pizza was replaced with veggie pizza, I understand it happens!).  2) Leadership team: Positive: When I would request a replacement of topping, they would. Bad experiences: After I reported the last two bad experiences (a hair in pizza bread and wrong order delivered), they refused my order that I placed 2 months after my last order! The reason I was told is that I had reported the two last bad experiences, so instead of correcting or apologizing, they chose to not deliver pizza in future to this customer!  As a loyal and a year long customer, I felt horrible today at the owner's response. Never expected such behavior from a professional Indian restaurant.

Simply phenomenal Vegan Options, Absolutely a beautiful place to dine. The staff is very professional, friendly and a great group of people. Peaceful, tranquil and an escape from all the rest. Food is beyond delicious 👍🏾.

Been in Boston thirty years, made pizza with old school Italians, it doesn't take a genius to make good pizza, just high standards and good ingredients. This place has fresh ingredients, you can see them behind the counter in the bottom refrigerators. I always get the vegetable hold the hot peppers and it always tastes great!  *Edit: Last time I ate here with my family we ordered two pizzas to dine inside. After waiting a long time for the pizza to arrive we received only one pizza and it was missing a couple ingredients listed on the menu. We ate that first pizza anyway and when the second pizza didn't show up yet we inquired about it and was told they thought we only ordered one pizza. It's not a big deal, just had to wait again. I dropped this place a star because they are getting sloppy. Will try here again soon hopefully they will improve on their service I like this place.  *Edit: the food here is still really good just not as good as the beginning. The pizzas don't have as many toppings like they used to. I can imagine times are tough because of covid-19, but still tastes great.

The pizza wasn’t great, the Bolognese was ok. The pizza tasted quite stale and was very dry, like pizza that had been left out for a day and reheated. I would skip this place for other vegetarian options around Boston.

Over last 10 years I have tried all kinda of paneer/Indian pizzas from  different cities in the US but this veggie crust Somerville by far the worst Indian style pizza I have ever tried. There was no flavor at all. Paneer was just plain paneer and not over roasted or marinated like it’s supposed in paneer tikka. Manchurian paneer pizza the same story, no flavor at all. Crust was also so thin. I’m not sure how come this place has so many positive reviews but could be because of other things. I would never ever try their over priced no flavor pizzas again.

Benefits of Veggie Crust: the existence of vegan pizza options, period. Their sauces are excellent, veggies are fresh. Having weird pizza variety is always a good thing though I always ask to leave *ginger* off my otherwise perfectly garlicky veggie pizza...  Drawbacks of Veggie Crust: they really skimp on the vegan cheese. It’s not at all covered to oozing like a regular pizza would be despite being an extra cost. And the cost for a pan is about $22-24. They don’t do any by the slice, and they don’t do anything smaller than a large.  So if I want a slice, I’ll go to Whole Foods on Beacon (.4 mi) for $3, or if I want a smaller vegan personal pie I’ll go to Beacon St Pizza (.3 mi) for $8.  But if someone else is paying, and we can order double vegan cheese, then yeah let’s go to Veggie Crust.

Great food, very customizable to whatever you feel! Several options for all flavor profiles. I would highly recommend the veggie panini. Light but filling and tasty :)

I had an avocado corn panini there a few weeks ago and had a tree but reaction and when I called them back several times they insisted that non of the food served contained any tree nuts. I had to go to the hospital and my doctor confirm that was a tree but allergic reaction.

The base dough was good too, not super thin but just thin enough and not too cheesy( I think it was some vegan cheese, not sure) which I liked . Definitely recommend it.

My kids and I love this place, both for casual dining in, and take-away. They have a pretty extensive menu, but 90% of the time we're just getting "junk food": pizza, fries, sometimes ice cream (they carry a bunch of FoMu flavors!).  I like their default white-flour crust, which is thin & airy (somewhere between Neapolitan and flatbread). I'm also a fan of their topping combos, many inspired by their Indian fusion sister restaurant next door, like cauliflower manchurian and tikka BBQ. Sauces are tasty, service is friendly and attentive. My main complaint about the pizza is the high upcharge for vegan cheese ($3 per pie). Since we can now get freshly-made pizza with 3 toppings and vegan cheese at Whole Foods for no extra markup, we are more likely to go there when thinking about the cost.

We tried the Pav Bhaji + Paneer Manchurian ( Half and Half) pizza. It was nice but not amazing. We also tried the Manchurian wedges. The wedges were cooked nicely but the Manchurian sauce wasn't that great. It was a little too tangy.
I just loved their dishes. I always get good service there. The place is always clean and the staff members are always very friendly. Will visit here again.
